<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-forming-quadratic-expressions-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Forming Quadratic Expressions in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Form quadratic expressions from different situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>
        Quadratic expressions often arise when working with area and geometric situations.
    </p>

    <activity>
        <title>Design a frame</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Imagine you are framing a picture for someone. The picture is 7 cm <m>\times</m> 5 cm, and you want to make a custom wood frame of uniform width <m>x</m> around all four sides. In terms of <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <image width="90%">
            <shortdescription>Framed picture with dimensions</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

                % Define colors
                \definecolor{frameColor}{RGB}{220, 220, 220} % Neutral gray
                \definecolor{photoColor}{RGB}{255, 255, 255} % White

                % 1. The Outer Frame (Total Area)
                \draw[thick, fill=frameColor] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);
                
                % 2. The Inner Photo
                \draw[thick, fill=photoColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,5);
                \node at (3.5, 2.5) {\textbf{5 $\times$ 7 Photo}};

                % 3. Dimension Arrows for the Frame Width (x)
                % Left side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (-1.5, 2.5) -- (0, 2.5) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                % Right side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (7, 2.5) -- (8.5, 2.5) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                % Top side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (3.5, 5) -- (3.5, 6.5) node[midway, right] {$x$};
                % Bottom side x
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, &gt;=Stealth] (3.5, 0) -- (3.5, -1.5) node[midway, right] {$x$};

                % 4. Total Dimension Labels
                % Total Width label at the bottom
                \draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=10pt, mirror}] (-1.5,-2) -- (8.5,-2) node[midway, below=10pt] {Total Length = $7 + 2x$};
                
                % Total Length label at the right
                \draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=10pt}] (9, 6.5) -- (9, -1.5) node[midway, right=10pt] {Total Width = $5 + 2x$};

            \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <ol>
                <li><p>What are the widths and height of the framed picture?</p></li>
                <li><p>What is the total area of the framed picture?</p></li>
                <li><p>What is the total area of the frame without the picture (in other words, how much wood do you need)?</p></li>
                <li><p>Write each of the expressions in standard form. Geometrically, what does the quadratic, linear and constant terms represent?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Conclusion</title>
        <p>
            In the picture below we can see which parts of the expression correspond to the different areas of the frame. The four corners (yellow) represent the <m>x^2</m> term, the four sides (blue) represent the <m>x</m> term, and the photo (white) represents the constant term:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Area = <m>4x^2 + 24x + 35</m></li>
            <li>1 photo: <m>35 \text{ cm}^2</m></li>
            <li>4 sides: <m>7x + 7x + 5x + 5x = 24x \text{ cm}^2</m></li>
            <li>4 corners: <m>4x^2 \text{ cm}^2</m></li>    
        </ul>
        <image width="80%">
            <shortdescription>Quadratic expression as area of a framed picture</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

                % Define colors
                \definecolor{cornerColor}{RGB}{255, 215, 0} % Gold
                \definecolor{sideColor}{RGB}{100, 180, 200}  % Teal-ish
                \definecolor{photoColor}{RGB}{240, 240, 240} % Light Gray

                % 1. The Original Photo (The Constant 'c')
                \fill[photoColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,5);
                \node at (3.5, 2.5) {\textbf{Photo (35)}};
                \draw (0,0) rectangle (7,5);

                % 2. The Side Strips (The Linear Term 'bx')
                % Top and Bottom strips
                \fill[sideColor] (0,5) rectangle (7,6.5);
                \fill[sideColor] (0,0) rectangle (7,-1.5);
                \node at (3.5, 5.75) {$7x$};
                \node at (3.5, -0.75) {$7x$};
                
                % Left and Right strips
                \fill[sideColor] (-1.5,0) rectangle (0,5);
                \fill[sideColor] (7,0) rectangle (8.5,5);
                \node[rotate=90] at (-0.75, 2.5) {$5x$};
                \node[rotate=270] at (7.75, 2.5) {$5x$};

                % 3. The Corners (The Quadratic Term 'ax^2')
                \fill[cornerColor] (-1.5,5) rectangle (0,6.5);   % Top-Left
                \fill[cornerColor] (7,5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);    % Top-Right
                \fill[cornerColor] (-1.5,0) rectangle (0,-1.5);  % Bottom-Left
                \fill[cornerColor] (7,0) rectangle (8.5,-1.5);   % Bottom-Right
                
                \node at (-0.75, 5.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (7.75, 5.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (-0.75, -0.75) {$x^2$};
                \node at (7.75, -0.75) {$x^2$};

                % Outlines for clarity
                \draw[dashed] (-1.5,-1.5) grid[step=1.5] (8.5,6.5);
                \draw[thick] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (8.5,6.5);

                % Labels for dimensions
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1.5, 7) -- (0, 7) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0, 7) -- (7, 7) node[midway, above] {$7$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (7, 7) -- (8.5, 7) node[midway, above] {$x$};
                
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 0) -- (-2.2, 5) node[midway, left] {$5$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 5) -- (-2.2, 6.5) node[midway, left] {$x$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.2, 0) -- (-2.2, -1.5) node[midway, left] {$x$};

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
    </paragraphs>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A rectangular garden has a length of <m>(x + 4)</m> metres and a width of <m>(x + 1)</m> metres.
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>Form an expression for the area of the garden.</li>
                    <li>Write the expression in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Area of a rectangle:
                <me>
                    \text{Area} = \text{length} \times \text{width}
                </me>
            </p>

            <p>
                Substitute the given expressions:
                <me>
                    (x + 4)(x + 1)
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Expand:
                <me>
                    x^2 + x + 4x + 4
                </me>
                <me>
                    = x^2 + 5x + 4
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                The area is expressed as a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-football-home-away">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A local football league has <m>n</m> teams. Each pair of teams plays two matches: one at Team A's home ground and one at Team B's home ground. How many matches are played in total? Express your answer as a quadratic expression in <m>n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Each of the <m>n</m> teams will play <m>n-1</m> matches in its home ground (one against each other team), because there are <m>n-1</m> other teams to play against (a team cannot play itself). So the total number of ordered matches is <m>n(n-1)</m> which expands to <m>n^2 - n</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The product of two consecutive integers is formed.
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>Represent the integers algebraically.</li>
                    <li>Form the expression for their product.</li>
                    <li>Write the result in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the first integer be <m>x</m>.
                The next consecutive integer is <m>x + 1</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Their product:
                <me>
                    x(x + 1)
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Expand:
                <me>
                    x^2 + x
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                This is a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A farmer wants to build a rectangular pen for goats. She has <m>60</m> metres of fencing 
                and will use an existing wall as one side of the pen. If the width of the pen 
                (perpendicular to the wall) is <m>x</m> metres:
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>Express the length of the pen in terms of <m>x</m>.</li>
                    <li>Form a quadratic expression for the area of the pen.</li>
                    <li>Write the expression in standard form.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since the wall forms one side, the farmer only needs fencing for three sides: 
                two widths and one length.
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + \text{length} \amp= 60</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{length} \amp= 60 - 2x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Finding the area of the rectangular pen:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \text{length} \times \text{width}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= (60 - 2x) \times x</mrow>
                    <intertext>Expanding:</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp= 60x - 2x^2</mrow>
                    <intertext>Writing in standard form (with <m>x^2</m> term first):</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp= -2x^2 + 60x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                This quadratic expression represents the area of the pen in square metres.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <insight>
        <title>Quadratic expressions describe interacting growth</title>
        <p>
            Quadratic expressions are not just numbers; they describe multidimensional growth. In many real-life
            situations a quadratic term appears because two independent linear factors interact with each other.
        </p>
        <p>
            A quadratic expression represents the accumulation of different types of growth in a single system:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <m>ax^2</m> term captures the "compounding" or "area" effect where a change in <m>x</m>
                    impacts the result in two directions at once (for example, the four corners of a frame or a
                    change that affects both price and quantity).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <m>bx</m> term captures linear growth, where a change in <m>x</m> affects only one dimension
                    (for example, side strips of a frame).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The constant term represents the baseline or starting state before any changes were made.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-forming-quadratic-expressions-in-real-life">
    
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            Form a quadratic expression for each situation and write your answer in standard form.
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    The area of a rectangle with length <m>(x + 3)</m> and width <m>(x + 2)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of a number and the number increased by <m>5</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of two numbers where one is <m>x</m> and the other is <m>(x - 4)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The area of a square with side length <m>(x + 6)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The area of a rectangle with length <m>(2x + 1)</m> and width <m>(x + 4)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of two consecutive even numbers.
                </li>
                <li>
                    A number is multiplied by three more than itself.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of <m>(x - 7)</m> and <m>(x + 2)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The area of a rectangular field whose length is <m>(x - 5)</m> metres 
                    and width is <m>(x + 3)</m> metres.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of two numbers whose difference is <m>4</m>, 
                    if the smaller number is <m>x</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The area of a square whose side length is <m>(3x - 2)</m>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The product of <m>(x + 1)</m>, <m>(x + 2)</m>, and <m>x</m>. 
                    (Expand fully.)
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= (x + 3)(x + 2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 2x + 3x + 6</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 5x + 6</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let the number be <m>x</m>. The number increased by <m>5</m> is <m>x + 5</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x + 5)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 5x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x - 4)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 - 4x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area of square} \amp= (x + 6)^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= (x + 6)(x + 6)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 6x + 6x + 36</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 12x + 36</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= (2x + 1)(x + 4)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 2x^2 + 8x + x + 4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 2x^2 + 9x + 4</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let the first even number be <m>x</m>. The next consecutive even number is <m>x + 2</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x + 2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 2x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let the number be <m>x</m>. Three more than itself is <m>x + 3</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x + 3)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 3x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= (x - 7)(x + 2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 2x - 7x - 14</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 - 5x - 14</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= (x - 5)(x + 3)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 3x - 5x - 15</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 - 2x - 15</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The smaller number is <m>x</m>. The larger number (difference of <m>4</m>) is <m>x + 4</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x + 4)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 4x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area of square} \amp= (3x - 2)^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= (3x - 2)(3x - 2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 9x^2 - 6x - 6x + 4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 9x^2 - 12x + 4</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding in stages:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Product} \amp= x(x + 1)(x + 2)</mrow>
                                <intertext>First expand <m>(x + 1)(x + 2) = x^2 + 3x + 2</m>, then multiply by <m>x</m>:</intertext>
                                <mrow>\amp= x(x^2 + 3x + 2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= x^3 + 3x^2 + 2x</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A mobile phone company is designing a new phone screen. The screen is rectangular 
                with a length that is <m>3</m> cm more than twice the width. If the width of the 
                screen is <m>x</m> cm:
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>Write an expression for the length of the screen.</li>
                    <li>Form a quadratic expression for the area of the screen.</li>
                    <li>If the company adds a <m>0.5</m> cm border around the screen, write 
                    the new dimensions and form an expression for the total area including the border.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The length is <m>3</m> cm more than twice the width.
                            <me>\text{Length} = 2x + 3 \text{ cm}</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>\text{Area} = \text{length} \times \text{width}</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= (2x + 3)(x)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 2x^2 + 3x \text{ square cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A <m>0.5</m> cm border on each side adds <m>1</m> cm to both width and length.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{New width} \amp= x + 1 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{New length} \amp= (2x + 3) + 1 = 2x + 4 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Total area} \amp= (x + 1)(2x + 4)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 2x^2 + 4x + 2x + 4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp= 2x^2 + 6x + 4 \text{ square cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>
    </exercises>
</subsubsection>